{"ts": "2026-06-07T21:20:26.838455+00:00", "update": {"tools": {"messages": [{"type": "tool", "data": {"content": [{"type": "text", "text": "{\"issues\":[{\"number\":1,\"title\":\"@Cache.cached returns stale value after the wrapped function\\u0026#39;s body changes\",\"body\":\"Hi — running into a workflow issue with `@Cache.cached()`. When I\\nupdate the body of a cached function during local development,\\nwalrus keeps returning the old cached value until I either restart\\nRedis, call `cache.bust()`, or change the function\\u0026#39;s args.\\n\\nMinimal example:\\n\\n    from walrus import Database\\n    db = Database()\\n    cache = db.cache()\\n\\n    @cache.cached(timeout=3600)\\n    def add(a, b):\\n        return a + b\\n\\n    # call once\\n    add(1, 2)   # 3, caches under key derived from \\u0026#34;add\\u0026#34; + args\\n\\n    # ... developer edits add() to return a * b ...\\n\\n    @cache.cached(timeout=3600)\\n    def add(a, b):\\n        return a * b\\n\\n    add(1, 2)   # still 3 (cached from previous body)\\n\\nMy read of `walrus/cache.py` is that the cache key is derived from\\nthe function\\u0026#39;s qualified name + args/kwargs hash, not from the\\nfunction\\u0026#39;s source / signature / body hash. So when the body\\nchanges but the name stays the same, the cached value sticks.\\n\\nThis is technically expected for any function-name-keyed cache,\\nbut for a dev-loop tool it\\u0026#39;s a sharp edge. README\\u0026#39;s \\u0026#34;Caching\\u0026#34;\\nsection doesn\\u0026#39;t call out this gotcha. Worth a docs note? Or is\\nthere an existing convention I missed (like cache.cached(name=...)\\nwith a versioned name)?\\n\\nwalrus 0.9.3, Redis 7.2, Python 3.11.\\n\\n---\\n\\nUpdate: dug around and figured out a `cache.bust()` pattern\\nworks for my dev-loop. Wrapped it in a tiny conftest fixture that\\nbusts a configurable list of cache keys at the start of each test\\nrun, and that solves the body-change-staleness for our use case.\\n\\nSo this is mostly just user-education on my side — the existing\\n`Cache.bust()` already covers what I needed. Sorry for the noise.\\n\\nClosing this from my side.\",\"state\":\"OPEN\",\"user\":{\"login\":\"BruceKZ\"},\"created_at\":\"2026-05-22T11:18:20Z\",\"updated_at\":\"2026-05-22T11:18:20Z\"}],\"totalCount\":1,\"pageInfo\":{\"hasNextPage\":false,\"hasPreviousPage\":false,\"startCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQxMToxODoyMFrPAAAAAQxZwwA=\",\"endCursor\":\"Y3Vyc29yOnYyOpK0MjAyNi0wNS0yMlQxMToxODoyMFrPAAAAAQxZwwA=\"}}", "id": "lc_2a34a371-42dc-493d-a6c2-5f3ef06dcb38"}], "additional_kwargs": {}, "response_metadata": {}, "type": "tool", "name": "list_issues", "id": "bc3e2eba-e62e-45bc-a14b-f2d0b02de40c", "tool_call_id": "call_00_AXLkTwqn4rBBdMMznJla1792", "artifact": null, "status": "success"}}]}}}
